// Regression: mudlib_error_handler() (src/vm/internal/simulate.cc) builds a
// diagnostic mapping to hand to the master's error handler. It held that
// mapping in a raw pointer and only pushed (transferred ownership) on the
// success path. If populating the mapping itself error()s -- e.g.
// mapping_too_large() when __MAX_MAPPING_SIZE__ is configured below what the
// ~6-entry diagnostic needs -- that second error() unwound with the mapping
// (and its keys/strings) leaked. Tracing that down also surfaced two more
// general leaks on the same throw paths: insert_in_mapping() not releasing a
// key's shared-string conversion, and load_mapping_from_aggregate() (backing
// mapping literals) not freeing the remaining pairs (the caller has already
// moved sp below the whole aggregate, hiding them from the normal unwind
// sweep). All are RAII/explicit-free fixed now.
//
// On a Debug build this is guarded by check_memory()'s post-file ref-count
// sweep: the unfixed driver reports "Bad ref count for mapping/string ..."
// after this file. On any build it must at least not crash. The test simply
// drives the path and restores the config; the leak detection is automatic.
void do_tests() {
  int orig_max = get_config(269);  // __MAX_MAPPING_SIZE__ (CFG_INT(13))

  // Shrink the mapping-size limit below what the error handler's own
  // diagnostic mapping needs, then trigger an error whose handling builds a
  // mapping literal (copy() of one) -- so both the error handler's mapping
  // and the literal's load_mapping_from_aggregate() hit the limit.
  set_config(269, 1);
  ASSERT2(catch(copy(([ "x": 1, "y": 2 ]))),
    "shrunk mapping-size limit should make this error");
  // Restore before asserting anything else, and unconditionally.
  set_config(269, orig_max);

  // A normal mapping works again with the limit restored -- proves nothing
  // was left in a broken state.
  ASSERT_EQ(2, sizeof(([ "a": 1, "b": 2 ])));
}
